fields.text: If there have been multiple instances or incidents of abuse, assault or troubling behavior that you wish to write about or make a record of, all involving the same individual, you may find it preferable to make a single record to contain all those incidents.  For that reason, you have the choice here of doing that, by selecting the appropriate response.

fields.descriptive_text: *If it has been less than 5 days, you may still be able to get a forensic exam to collect potential evidence (in the case of a sexual assault).  Learn more here about the forensic exam (“rape kit”).

fields.descriptive_text: Examples include the exact address, intersection, building number or name, surrounding location, building or specific room in a building or house, etc.

fields.text:
You may have physical or electronic evidence.
If you ever choose to report what happened to your school or the police, they may ask you for electronic and/or physical evidence of what happened.  If you don't have these things, it doesn't mean that what happened is any less real, and it doesn’t prevent you from reporting, receiving support, and activating measures to enhance your safety and the safety of the community, including no-contact orders and seeking other outcomes or judgments.
fields.descriptive_text:
Below is information on different types of evidence and how to preserve them in case you want or need it later.
Electronic evidence includes things like emails photos/videos text messages screenshots electronic medical records social media interactions (Twitter, Facebook, Snapchat, Instagram, etc.).
Physical evidence includes things like clothing bedsheets condoms medical records any evidence collected as part of a forensic exam (“rape kit”)
Save screenshots and the original of any electronic evidence in a folder on your computer or in another storage form to which only you have access. Place each item of potential physical evidence in its own paper bag (plastic bags can eliminate DNA) and store someplace only you can access (i.e. out of common spaces, away from roommates).

fields.text: Which of the following apply? (check all that apply)
If you wish, include any details about the physical or electronic evidence that you may have.

You may have experienced sexual contact of some kind that feels abusive, unwanted or nonconsensual.  Or you may have experienced troubling behavior with an intimate partner, with someone you dated or are dating, or in some other kind of relationship, actions that could be construed as harassment, verbal or emotional abuse and/or violence.  This next question will ask you to consider or note what reflects your experience.   If you feel that you have experienced some of each within a single incident, you may readily record that in a single narrative or in separate narratives, whichever you prefer.
fields.descriptive_text: Nonconsensual sexual contact is never okay. Nonconsensual contact is never your fault. Consent to sexual activity can be given by word or action, and just because you didn’t say no, doesn’t mean you gave consent. You can consent to one thing without consenting to another thing, and you can withdraw consent at any time, from any person. Learn more about Grinnell's definition of affirmative consent here.

fields.text: Does nonconsensual sexual contact apply to your experience?
If appropriate, which of the following apply to your experience? (please check all that apply)

You may have experienced words or actions that are troubling, and are unsure what to call them, to say whether they constitute verbal, emotional or psychological abuse.  You may have experienced stalking or other forms of harassment.   You may have experienced physical violence or the threat of it.  This may have taken place within an intimate partner relationship, within a dating relationship, or in some other type of relationship.  You may feel anger, fear, loss of control over your situation, minimized, or other emotional distresses.  You may also feel care, compassion and love, even while feeling or knowing that something is wrong.  If you are feeling any of this, we encourage you to reach out to someone who can provide a safe and confidential space for you to speak of your experiences and concerns.
fields.descriptive_text: Click here for links to and more information about your confidential resources, including the hotlines for the Grinnell College Peer Advocates, Crisis Intervention Services, and the Crisis Center, and on-campus confidential resources including the chaplains, the ombuds, counselors at SHACS, and peer Advocates.

fields.text: Does intimate partner or dating abuse or violence, or harassment possibly apply to your experience?
If appropriate, which of the follow apply to your experience?  (please check all that apply)
Your school has an Amnesty Policy (link), which means if you choose to report what happened, you will not get in trouble with your school even if you were drinking underage or using illegal drugs.
fields.descriptive_text:
Among many possible involvements, substance use may prevent a person from being capable of giving consent, may be used by one person to manipulate another, or may be associated with abusive or violent behavior.  If alcohol and/or drugs were involved, your choice (if you did choose) to use such substances does not mean that you chose to experience what followed or that you are responsible for what happened.

Should you decide to take part in any investigation (for more information about investigations, you can follow this link), the involvement of alcohol and/or drugs could be very helpful information in ascertaining responsibility and consequences for the other person(s). 
    
If you are comfortable, please include anything about drugs and alcohol that are related to your experience, by responding to the following two prompts:

fields.text: Were alcohol or drugs involved? (please check all that apply)
Tell us anything you can remember about this.
fields.descriptive_text: If you can remember anything around what substances (legal or illegal) were taken or what you think was taken, please write it here.

fields.text: Were there witnesses or others who know of the incident?
fields.descriptive_text: Did you tell anyone about the incident(s)?

fields.text: If you feel comfortable right now indicating who you told, you can enter it here.
Did you notice any witnesses to any part of the incident(s)?

Here you can enter any information you have about people you told or about witnesses to the incident(s).  As a reminder, the record you are creating is absolutely secure and confidential.  The only way in which this information can be shared is if you choose to share it or if you choose to report this record to your school’s Title IX office.  If you ever want to report in the future, witnesses, bystanders or people you told any part of what you have experienced can help greatly in an investigation.

This may be the hardest part. We are so sorry this has happened to you and want to make this process as comfortable as possible. Take a moment if you need it or skip this part and return to it later to finish.
fields.descriptive_text: If you wish, you can visit support services for suggestions for self-care and options for speaking with someone.

It is okay if you're not sure, just put what you can remember.

fields.descriptive_text: Like everything else in this record, this answer is just for you, unless you decide to share it with the Title IX office - it is encrypted and stored securely such that no one but you can view it.  Also, putting their name here does not enter it into matching.  You can do that separately on your dashboard, if you choose.

fields.text: Include any relevant information about the perpetrator you’d like to save.
fields.descriptive_text: Examples include any physical characteristics, hair color, identifiable marks, tattoos, clothing, if you’ve seen them before, or anything you could not forget about them.
